The given grammar is in Chomsky normal form, so every derivation of the 20-token string must have a binary-branching parse tree whose leaves are exactly the 20 terminals:

t40  t110  t51  t2  t17  t108  t97  t48  t97  t32  t33  t67  t108  t17  t17  t13  t89  t80  t13  t24

Step 1 – terminals and the only non-terminals that can generate them  
(only the productions of the form NT → 'token' are relevant here):

t40 → NT5  
t110 → NT14  
t51 → NT33, NT40  
t2 → NT0, NT11, NT18  
t17 → NT12  
t108 → NT37  
t97 → NT22  
t48 → NT35  
t32 → NT12, NT23  
t33 → NT13  
t67 → NT21, NT20  
t13 → NT26  
t89 → NT51  
t80 → NT44  
t24 → NT17, NT19  

Step 2 – length-two substrings  

In a CNF grammar, every constituent covering two consecutive terminals must be licensed by a single binary rule A → B C where B covers the first token and C the second.  Looking at all binary rules in the grammar, none combines the pairs

(NT5, NT14) (t40 t110) positions 1–2  
(NT14, NT33/NT40) (t110 t51) positions 2–3  
(NT33/NT40, NT0/NT11/NT18) (t51 t2) positions 3–4  

and so on.  In fact, for every one of the nineteen adjacent pairs of tokens, inspection of the binary rules shows that there is no non-terminal that can derive the pair in a single step.  Because a CNF parse tree must combine adjacent leaves two at a time, the failure to find even one valid length-two constituent already blocks every possible larger constituent, including any that could span the entire 20-token string.

Step 3 – consequences for the start symbol  

Since no binary constituent of length 2 exists, no constituent of any longer length can be built, and therefore the start symbol S cannot derive the whole string.

Conclusion: the string is not in the language generated by the grammar.

No

The last symbol of the string is t108.  
In this grammar the ONLY non-terminal that can produce t108 directly is  

  NT37 → 't108'

Consequently, in any derivation of the whole string the right–most symbol must be
NT37 and the start production must be

  S → NT27 NT37                                     (1)

(the other four rules for S put some non-terminal different from NT37 in the
right-most position, and none of those can generate t108).

So NT27 has to generate the first 18 tokens

 t22 t110 t106 t34 t80 t110 t94 t80 t41 t14 t87 t21 t95 t31 t76 t19 t46 t111.

Examining the rules for NT27 we have only two possible binary productions:

 NT27 → NT31 NT20            (2)  
 NT27 → NT34 NT9             (3)

(The remaining rules for NT27 are single-terminal rules, which would give a
string of length 1 and are therefore impossible.)

Case (2).  
NT20 can only generate one of the six single terminals  
t54, t28, t76, t46, t106, t67.  
Hence (2) can generate at most two terminals – far fewer than the required 18.
So (2) is impossible.

Case (3).  
For the first symbol to be t22 we must use

 NT34 → NT31 NT24    and   NT31 → 't22'.

After producing t22, the next symbol (the second one) has to be t110.
The only way NT24 can start with t110 is

 NT24 → NT14 NT35    with   NT14 → 't110'.

Thus the third symbol has to be produced by NT35.
The productions for NT35 are

 NT35 → NT6 NT47 | NT13 NT28 | NT28 NT47 | NT43 NT34 | NT42 NT40 | NT35 NT17  
 NT35 → 't103' | 't81' | 't22' | 't0'.

None of the single-terminal alternatives gives t106, so the first block must be
one of the binary alternatives.  
Checking each binary alternative one sees that the very first terminal that can
be produced is one of

 t84 (NT6), t74/t34/t61/t73 (NT13), t3 (NT28), t111/t103/t46 (NT43),  
 t80 (NT42→NT44), …

but NEVER t106.  
Therefore NT35 can not begin with t106, and hence NT27 cannot produce the
required third symbol t106.

Since both possible binary rules for NT27 are impossible, NT27 cannot generate
the required 18-symbol prefix, and consequently the whole string cannot be
produced from S.

Hence the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No
